article.description: Ray Allen scored 32 points and moved into a tie for second place on the NBA's career 3-pointers list as the SuperSonics beat the Rockets 104-87.
article.headline: Allen moves into tie for second in career 3-pointers
article.linkText: Allen moves into tie for second in career 3-pointers
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- When Seattle acquired Chris Wilcox, coach Bob Hill told him he needed to average 16 points and eight rebounds to be a viable power forward in the NBA. Wilcox was more than just viable Tuesday night, finishing with 26 points and 24 rebounds in the SuperSonics' 104-87 win over the Houston Rockets. Ray Allen also scored 32 points for Seattle and moved into a tie for second place on the NBA's career 3-pointers list. "His upside is a joke," Hill said of Wilcox. "He could be really special." Wilcox tied Phoenix's Shawn Marion for the most rebounds in a game in the league this season, and his career-high total was the most by a Sonics player since Jack Sikma gathered 25 in 1983. Wilcox is the ninth Sonics player to have 20 points and 20 rebounds in a game and the first since Shawn Kemp on Nov. 15, 1995. Hill said he regretted not pulling Wilcox in the final seconds to get an ovation from the crowd. "For me it was all about opportunity. I never got an opportunity to play," said Wilcox, who averaged just 13 minutes with the Los Angeles Clippers this season before getting traded to Seattle on Feb. 14. Wilcox entered Tuesday's game averaging 14 points, seven rebounds and 29 minutes with the Sonics. "The league really didn't know my talent," he said. The league knows all about Allen. The six-time All-Star moved even with Dale Ellis, who played six-plus seasons for Seattle, for second all-time with 1,719 3-pointers. Allen shot 11-for-22 and made three 3s, all in the second half. Reggie Miller is the all-time leader with 2,560. "Records are always made to be broken," Allen said. "I know Reggie, he's sitting up there, but I figure I have a long way to go, many more games and many more 3s to hit." Yao Ming led the Rockets with 22 points and 10 rebounds, but fouled out with 11:31 left and was outplayed on the interior by Wilcox. Yao was called for his sixth foul on Rashard Lewis' baseline drive with the Rockets trailing 79-68. Stromile Swift scored on Houston's next possession, but Seattle went on an 11-2 run and the Rockets never threatened. Yao had not fouled out since Dec. 11 at Portland. "I don't understand my fouls. I don't understand it, it's a normal action," he said. Houston had won six straight against Seattle and was trying to sweep the season series for the first time since the teams started playing in the 1967-68 season. The Rockets have lost the first two games of a six-game trip. "We played a very soft, non-contact game," Houston coach Jeff Van Gundy said. "We had Wilcox jumping over us the whole game." Lewis added 10 points for the Sonics off the bench. He had missed two of the last three games with a sprained right ankle, and came off the bench for the first time since Nov. 25, 2001. Lewis had started the previous 354 games he'd played. Neither team resembled the squads that met last Wednesday in Houston. That Seattle team was physically drained, playing the second game of a back-to-back and following last second wins over San Antonio and Memphis. Seattle had no answer for Yao, who finished with 29 points and 10 rebounds in a 115-87 Rockets win, their biggest margin of victory at home this season. Tuesday, the Sonics guarded the 7-foot-6 center with three or four defenders at times. Unlike last week when six Rockets scored in double figures, Yao got little help. Rafer Alston scored 16 and Juwan Howard added 13 and 10 rebounds. Despite giving up eight inches to Yao, it was Wilcox dominating inside. The 6-foot-10 forward had 16 points and 13 rebounds in the first half, and was credited with two blocks, including a swat of a short jumper by Yao. He tied his previous career high of 19 rebounds with 5 minutes left in the third quarter and collected his 20th moments later.

Game notes
Seattle broadcaster Kevin Calabro called his 1,500th game with the Sonics on Tuesday. The first Sonics broadcast for Calabro was Nov. 6, 1987, when Seattle visited the Los Angeles Lakers. The Indiana native is in his 19th season with the Sonics. ... Former Sonics Richie Frahm and Rick Brunson combined for 13 points off Houston's bench. ... Seattle rookie C Johan Petro didn't play after breaking his nose Sunday against Portland. He's scheduled to have surgery Wednesday.
